import GuideLayout from '../../layouts/GuideLayout.astro'
const content = `
<div class="prose prose-gray max-w-none dark:prose-invert prose-headings:text-gray-900 dark:prose-headings:text-white prose-p:text-gray-600 dark:prose-p:text-gray-400 prose-strong:text-gray-900 dark:prose-strong:text-white prose-code:text-blue-600 dark:prose-code:text-blue-400 prose-a:text-blue-600 dark:prose-a:text-blue-400 prose-li:text-gray-600 dark:prose-li:text-gray-400 prose-pre:bg-gray-50 dark:prose-pre:bg-gray-900 prose-pre:border prose-pre:border-gray-200 dark:prose-pre:border-gray-800">

<p>This tutorial shows you how to generate a password that is actually strong — not "has a capital letter and an exclamation mark" strong, but resistant to billions of guesses per second. It takes about a minute, and the settings you choose matter more than the button you click.</p>

<h2>Step 1: Open the Generator and Set the Length</h2>
<p>Open the <a href="/tools/password-generator/">Password Generator</a>. The first setting — length — is the one that matters most. Set it to <strong>at least 16 characters</strong>; 20 is better for anything important.</p>
<p>Here's why length beats complexity. Each added character multiplies the number of possible passwords by the alphabet size. Compare:</p>
<ul>
  <li>8 characters, all four character types (95-symbol alphabet): 95<sup>8</sup> ≈ 6.6 × 10<sup>15</sup> possibilities</li>
  <li>16 characters, lowercase only (26-symbol alphabet): 26<sup>16</sup> ≈ 4.4 × 10<sup>22</sup> possibilities</li>
</ul>
<p>The longer, simpler password has roughly <strong>6.7 million times</strong> more possibilities than the shorter, complex one. A cracking rig testing 100 billion guesses per second exhausts the 8-character space in under a day; the 16-character space would take thousands of years. When a site's policy forces complexity, satisfy it — but get your security from length.</p>

<h2>Step 2: Choose Character Sets</h2>
<p>Enable uppercase, lowercase, digits, and symbols for maximum entropy per character. Two practical adjustments:</p>
<ul>
  <li><strong>Site rejects symbols?</strong> Some legacy systems only accept certain symbols or none. Disable the symbols set and add 4 characters of length instead — that more than compensates.</li>
  <li><strong>Password must be typed by hand?</strong> For a Wi-Fi password you'll read off to guests or type on a TV remote, consider excluding look-alike characters (<code>l</code>, <code>1</code>, <code>I</code>, <code>O</code>, <code>0</code>) if the generator offers it, or use lowercase + digits only at greater length. Typing <code>kX9#mQ2$vL8@</code> on a game controller is misery.</li>
</ul>

<h2>Step 3: Generate and Check the Strength</h2>
<p>Click <strong>Generate</strong>. You'll get something like:</p>
<pre><code>Vq7#tRk2$mXw9!pZ</code></pre>
<p>Run it through the <a href="/tools/password-strength/">Password Strength Checker</a> to see the estimated entropy and crack time. A good target is <strong>80+ bits of entropy</strong> — a 16-character password from a 95-symbol alphabet gives about 105 bits, comfortably beyond any brute-force capability.</p>
<p>Generation happens locally in your browser using <code>crypto.getRandomValues()</code>, the cryptographically secure random source — the password never travels over the network. That's the property that makes a browser-based generator acceptable for real credentials.</p>

<h2>Step 4: Store It — Don't Memorize It</h2>
<p>A generated password is only practical with a password manager (1Password, Bitwarden, KeePassXC, or your browser's built-in manager). The workflow that actually works:</p>
<ol>
  <li>Generate the password.</li>
  <li>Paste it into the site's signup/change-password form <em>and</em> into your password manager in the same minute.</li>
  <li>Never reuse it anywhere else.</li>
</ol>
<p>The one password you do memorize is your password manager's master password. For that, a generated 16-character string is hostile to memory; use a <strong>passphrase</strong> instead — four to six random words like <code>brick-otter-plume-vivid-canyon</code>. At ~12.9 bits per word from a 7,776-word list (the Diceware standard), five words give ~64 bits, and six give ~77 bits, while remaining typeable and memorable.</p>

<h2>Generating Passwords Without the Tool</h2>
<pre><code># macOS / Linux — 24 random Base64 characters
openssl rand -base64 24

# Linux — 20 chars from an explicit character set
tr -dc 'A-Za-z0-9!@#$%^&*' &lt; /dev/urandom | head -c 20; echo

# Python 3
python3 -c "import secrets, string; print(''.join(secrets.choice(string.ascii_letters + string.digits + '!@#$%^&*') for _ in range(20)))"</code></pre>
<p>Note the Python version uses the <code>secrets</code> module, not <code>random</code> — <code>random</code> is predictable and must never generate credentials. The same rule applies in every language: JavaScript's <code>Math.random()</code>, PHP's <code>rand()</code>, and C's <code>rand()</code> are all wrong for passwords.</p>

<h2>Common Problems and Fixes</h2>
<h3>The site silently truncates long passwords</h3>
<p>Some systems cut passwords at 16, 20, or 72 bytes (bcrypt's limit) without telling you — then the login fails because you typed the full version. If a fresh password immediately fails, try logging in with the first 16 or 20 characters. Long-term fix: check the site's stated maximum and generate exactly to it.</p>
<h3>Password rejected for containing "invalid characters"</h3>
<p>The site's form or backend can't handle certain symbols (often quotes, backslashes, or angle brackets — a smell of poor escaping on their end). Regenerate with symbols disabled and length increased. A 20-character alphanumeric password (~119 bits) is stronger than a 12-character anything.</p>
<h3>"Password was found in a data breach" warning</h3>
<p>Your browser or manager checks new passwords against breach corpora like Have I Been Pwned. A freshly generated 16-character random password will essentially never trigger this; if it does, you're likely reusing an old password instead of the generated one. Generate a new one and update the manager entry.</p>
<h3>I need many passwords at once</h3>
<p>Provisioning test accounts or seeding a user table? Generate in bulk with the CLI commands above in a loop, or click generate repeatedly and collect. For test fixtures where security doesn't matter, the <a href="/tools/random-string/">Random String Generator</a> does batches natively.</p>

<h2>FAQ</h2>
<h3>How long should a password be in 2026?</h3>
<p>16 characters minimum for accounts that matter (email, banking, cloud consoles), 20+ for anything protecting other credentials. Current NIST guidance (SP 800-63B) emphasizes length over composition rules and recommends supporting passwords up to at least 64 characters.</p>
<h3>Are password generators safe to use?</h3>
<p>A generator that runs client-side with a cryptographically secure random source is safe — verify by checking that the page works offline (disconnect Wi-Fi and generate; this tool does). Avoid any generator that produces the password on a server, because then the server saw your password.</p>
<h3>Random password or passphrase — which is stronger?</h3>
<p>Character-for-character, random strings pack more entropy. But strength comparisons only matter at equal memorability: for anything stored in a manager, use random strings; for the handful you must type from memory, a 5–6 word passphrase wins because you'll actually use it instead of writing it on a sticky note.</p>
<h3>How is my password protected after I set it?</h3>
<p>Properly built sites never store the password itself — they store a slow hash (bcrypt, scrypt, or Argon2) and compare hashes at login. That's why sites reset passwords rather than email you the old one. The <a href="/guides/password-hash-guide/">password and hash guide</a> explains how hashing, salting, and cracking economics work, and the <a href="/tools/bcrypt-hash/">Bcrypt Hash tool</a> lets you see it in action.</p>
</div>
